This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with the problem of recommending a sequence of items to maximize user utility. It also involves training an Evaluator on user logs to predict the expected feedback of each item, which is a common technique used in information retrieval. 

The paper could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it proposes a new ranking framework called the Evaluator-Generator framework, which involves training a model to predict user feedback and generating different sequences from which the model chooses the final recommendation. 

The Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper deals with the problem of selecting and ordering items in a feed, which is a common problem in natural language processing tasks such as text summarization and generation. 

The Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category is another possibility as the paper deals with the problem of recommending items to users, which is a common problem in social networks and online platforms. 

Finally, the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category is a less likely possibility as the paper does not explicitly deal with security or privacy issues, but it could be relevant if the proposed framework is used in a secure or privacy-preserving manner.
